{{Infobox cemetery | name = Budapest Turkish Memorial Cemetery | image = | imagesize = | caption = | map_type = Budapest | map_size = 100 | map_caption = Location of Budapest Turkish Memorial Cemetery. | established = 1926 | country = [[Hungary]] | location = [[Kőbánya]], [[Budapest]] | coordinates = {{coord|47.472|19.189|display=inline}} | type = Turkish military of WWI | style = | owner = | size = {{convert|4598|m2|acre|abbr=on}} | graves = 480 | website = | findagrave = | political = }}
The '''Budapest Turkish Memorial Cemetery''' ({{lang-tr|Budapeşte Türk Şehitliği}}) is a burial ground of [[Military of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman soldiers]] in [[Hungary]]. It is situated as a section within [[Budapest]]'s largest cemetery of [[New Public Cemetery, Budapest|New Public Cemetery]] ({{lang-hu|Új köztemető}}) at [[Kőbánya]] district of the city. Ottoman soldiers are buried in the cemetery, who participated on the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Galicia front]] during the [[World War I]].
Established in 1926, the Turkish Memorial Cemetery holds 480 soldiers of [[Ottoman Army]]'s [[XV Corps (Ottoman Empire)|XV Corps]], who fought in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]] as part of the [[Central Powers]] under the command of [[South Army (German Empire)|German Empire's South Army]] in the summer of 1916. Eleven graves are of unknown soldiers. The cemetery is walled and covers an area of {{convert|4598|m2|acre|abbr=on}} with a graveyard section of {{convert|1718|m2|acre|abbr=on}}. A plate on the entrance denotes the property. The [[flag of Turkey]] waves on a flagpole in the cemetery.<ref name="dib">{{cite web |url=http://budapest.emb.mfa.gov.tr/ShowInfoNotes.aspx?ID=121443 |publisher=Dışişleri Bakanlığı |title=Budapeşte hakkında bilgiler, 15.06.2012 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-09-30 }}</ref>
Commemoration ceremonies are held at site every year on March 18, the [[Martyrs' Day#Turkey|Martyrs' Day in Turkey]], by Turkish officials<ref>{{cite news |url=http://hurarsiv.hurriyet.com.tr/goster/haber.aspx?id=4100284&tarih=2006-03-17 |newspaper=[[Hürriyet]] |title=Çanakkale şehitleri Budapeşte'de anıldı |date=2006-03-17 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-09-30 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://avrupa.hurriyet.com.tr/haberler/arsiv-haberler/138694/budapestete-turk-sehitleri-anildi |newspaper=[[Hürriyet]] |title=Budapeşte'te Türk şehitleri anıldı |date=2008-03-19 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-09-30 }}</ref> and on November 1, the [[All Saints' Day]], by Hungarians.<ref name="dib"/> High ranked Turkish politicians officially visiting Budapest pay tribute to the burials at the Turkish Cemetery.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timeturk.com/tr/2013/09/14/bakan-celik-galicya-cephesi-sehitligi-ni-ziyaret-etti.html |newspaper=Time Türk |title=Bakan Çelik, Galiçya Cephesi Şehitliği'ni ziyaret etti |date=2013-09-14 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-09-30 }}</ref>
For the preservation and maintenance of the memorial cemetery, the Turkish Military Cemeteries and Memorials Department ({{lang-tr|Şehitlikler ve Anıtlar Şubesi}}) of the Ministry of Family and Social Policies is responsible.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sehityakinlari.aile.gov.tr/tr/5050/Myanmar-Turk-Sehitlikleri-Yapim-Projesi |publisher=Aile ve Sosyal Politikalar Bakanlığı |title=Myanmar Türk Şehitlikleri Yapım Projesi |language=Turkish |accessdate=2013-09-29 }}</ref>
