{{for|the surname|Ciorbă (surname)}}
{{Infobox prepared food | name = Ciorbă | image = Ciorba.jpg | image_size = 220px | imagesize = 250px | caption = A bowl of ciorbă | alternate_name = | country = [[Romania]] | region = | creator = | course = [[Entrée]], [[Main course]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Water]], [[vegetable]]s, ''[[Borș (bran)|borș]]'', [[spice]]s | variations = Made with [[meat]], [[Fish as food|fish]], or [[Liver (food)|liver]] | calories = | other = }}
'''Ciorbă''' ({{IPA-ro|ˈt͡ʃʲorbə}}), from [[Persian language|Persian]] ''shorba'' (شوربا) via [[Turkish language|Turkish]] ''çorba'' is a general [[Romanian language|Romanian]] word used in [[Romania|Romania]] and the [[Republic of Moldova|Republic of Moldova]] to describe [[sour soup]]s consisting of various vegetables and meat. Most people differentiate between "supă" (soup) and "ciorbă" by the fact that ''supă'' has no added acid and is usually clear (with only one exception), while ''ciorbă'' may contain a wide variety of sour ingredients, usually [[lemon]]s, ''[[Borș (bran)|borș]]'', or ''zeamă de varză acră'' ([[sauerkraut]] juice). In [[Moldavia]] region, the word ''borș'' means simply any [[sour soup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/iasi/teorii-istorie-culinara-dezamagesc-borsul-mujdeiul-singurele-alimente-adevarat-romanesti-micii-inventati-cocosatu-mit-urban-1_55b8ee1df5eaafab2c10137a/index.html|title=Teorii de istorie culinară care ne dezamăgesc: borşul şi mujdeiul, singurele alimente cu adevărat româneşti. Micii inventaţi de Cocoşatu' – un mit urban|website=Adevarul.ro|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> [[Lovage]] is a frequent addition.
Ciorbă is a widespread and popular dish in Romania, and is occasionally considered to have beneficual health effects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.historia.ro/sectiune/general/articol/supa-si-ciorba-scurta-istorie|title=Supa şi ciorba: scurtă istorie|website=Historia.ro|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> When served hot it is thought to stimulate digestion and be effective against colds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://a1.ro/lifestyle/food/ce-ciorba-prefera-sa-manance-romanii-id734738.html|title=Ce ciorbă preferă să mănânce românii|website=A1.ro|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref>
In 2013 18 percent of respondents in a national poll in Romania declared ciorbă their favourite dish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ziare.com/social/romani/ce-obiceiuri-alimentare-au-romanii-sondaj-ires-1236034|title=Ce obiceiuri alimentare au romanii - sondaj IRES|website=Ziare.com|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref>
[[File:Ciorba de vacuta.jpg|270px|right|thumb|Beef ciorbă served with [[sour cream]] and [[Chili pepper|chili]]]]
Types of ciorbă include: * [[Ciorbă de burtă]] ([[tripe]] soup) * Ciorbă de rasol * Ciorbă de fasole ([[bean]] soup) * Ciorbă de cartofi (potato soup) * Ciorbă de ciocănele (soup made from chicken legs) * [[Ciorbă de perişoare]] ([[meatball]] soup) * Ciorbă de peşte (fish soup) * [[Ciorbă de praz]] (leek soup) * [[Ciorbă de pui]] (chicken soup) * Ciorbă de oase (bones soup) * [[Ciorbă de sfeclă]] (Romanian [[borscht]]) * Ciorbă de văcuţă (beef soup) * [[Borş de burechiuşe]]
==See also== * [[Borș (bran)|Borș]] * [[Chorba]] * [[List of soups]]
