{{See also|Serbia#Climate|Geography of Serbia#Climate}}
The '''Serbian climate''' is between a continental climate in the north, with cold winters, and hot, humid summers with well distributed rainfall patterns, and a more Adriatic climate in the south with hot, dry summers and autumns and rank daily average relatively cold winters with heavy inland snowfall. Differences in elevation, proximity to the [[Adriatic Sea]] and large river basins, as well as exposure to the winds account for climate differences.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-92892/Serbia |title=Serbia :: Climate |accessdate= |year=2007 |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica Online |pages=5 of 71 }}</ref>
Northern Serbia possesses typical continental climate, with air masses from northern and western Europe which shape its climatic profile. South and South-west Serbia is subject to Mediterranean influences. However, the [[Dinaric Alps]] and other mountain ranges contribute to the cooling down of most of the warm air masses. Winters are quite harsh in [[Raška (region)|Raška]] (region) because of the mountains which encircle the plateau.<ref>Radovanović, M and Dučić, V, 2002, [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2002EGSGA..27.2283R Variability of Climate in Serbia in the Second Half of the 20th century], EGS XXVII General Assembly, Nice, 21 April to 26 April 2002, abstract #2283, '''27''':2283–, provided by the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] / [[NASA]] Astrophysics Data System</ref> Mediterranean micro-regions exist throughout southern Serbia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ri.html |title=The World Factbook |website=Cia.gov |date= |accessdate=2016-04-14}}</ref> in Zlatibor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpk-uzice.co.rs/en/tourism/index.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 30, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315155231/http://www.rpk-uzice.co.rs/en/tourism/index.php |archivedate=March 15, 2012 }}</ref> and the Pčinja District around valley and river [[Pčinja (river)|Pčinja]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://travel2serbia.com/rivers%20/river-pcinja-valley |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 10, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918082907/http://travel2serbia.com/rivers%20/river-pcinja-valley |archivedate=September 18, 2009 }}</ref> The average annual air temperature for the period 1961–90 for the area with an altitude of up to {{convert|300|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} is {{convert|10.9|°C|lk=on}}. The areas with an altitude of {{convert|300|to|500|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} have an average annual temperature of around {{convert|10.0|°C}}, and over {{convert|1000|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} of altitude around {{convert|6.0|°C|1}}.<ref name="RHMZ">{{cite web |url=http://www.hidmet.gov.rs/eng/meteorologija/klimatologija_srbije.php |title=Basic Climate Characteristics for the Territory of Serbia |accessdate= |publisher=Republic Hydrometeorological Service of Serbia }}</ref> The lowest recorded temperature in Serbia was {{convert|-39.5|°C}} (January 13, 1985, [[Karajukića Bunari]] in [[Pešter]]), and the highest was {{convert|45|C|F|disp=or}} (July 24, 2007, [[Zajecar]]).<ref name="RHMZ"/>

