{{Politics of Liechtenstein}}
'''General elections''' were held in [[Liechtenstein]] on 3 and 5 March 1989. The result was a victory for the [[Patriotic Union (Liechtenstein)|Patriotic Union]], which won 13 of the 25 seats in the [[Landtag of Liechtenstein|Landtag]], which had been enlarged by 10 seats compared to the [[Liechtenstein parliamentary election, 1986|1986 elections]]. Voter turnout was 90.88%.<ref>[http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/arc/2187_89.htm Liechtenstein] Inter-Parliamentary Union</ref> This was the first and only election contested by the [[Non-Party List]], a political grouping attempting to prevent either the VU or FBP from forming a majority.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Parties: Political landscape after 1945|url=http://www.fuerstundvolk.li/fuv/fuv.do?site=421173216f221000996d610c1957690b|work=Prince and People: Liechtenstein Civics|publisher=School Office of the Principality of Liechtenstein|year=2007|accessdate=13 February 2014|language=German}}</ref>
==Results== {| class=wikitable style=text-align:right !Party !Votes !% !Seats !+/– |- |align=left|[[Patriotic Union (Liechtenstein)|Patriotic Union]]||75,417||47.2||13||+5 |- |align=left|[[Progressive Citizens' Party in Liechtenstein|Progressive Citizens' Party]]||67,382||42.1||12||+5 |- |align=left|[[Free List (Liechtenstein)|Free List]]||12,090||7.6||0||0 |- |align=left|[[Non-Party List]]||5,061||3.2||0||New |- |align=left|Invalid/blank votes||137||–||–||– |- |align=left|'''Total'''||'''12,082'''||'''100'''||'''25'''||'''+10''' |- |align=left|Registered voters/turnout||13,307||90.8||–||– |- |align=left colspan=5|Source: Nohlen & Stöver<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] & Stöver, P (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', pp1181–1183 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> |}
Note that the total number of votes is lower than the total for the parties, as each voter has as many votes as there are seats in a constituency, and thus can cast multiple votes.
