==Bangladesh== {{Main|Bangladeshi cuisine}}
{| class="wikitable sortable" width="100%" ! Name ! class="unsortable"| Image ! Description |- | [[Bihari cuisine#Non-vegetarian cuisine|Bihari kabab]] | [[File:Bihari Kabab.JPG|127px]] | Skewered pieces hunks or strips of lean beef, [[Marination|marinated]] in spices, yogurts and chillies and tenderised to perfection before slowly grilled on a charcoal flame . The dish was brought from [[Bihar]], [[India]]. (see [[Biharis in Bangladesh]]).<ref name="Bihari kabab">{{cite web|url=http://pakistaniat.com/2006/11/09/bihari-kabab-the-runaway-chicken/|title=Bihari kabab|work=ALL THINGS PAKISTAN|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref> |- | [[Chicken tikka|Tikka kebab]] | [[File:Chicken Tikka (1).jpg|127px]] | Made of chunks of grilled chicken marinated with yogurts, sauces and spices.<ref name="Oseland 2011 124">{{cite book | last=Oseland | first=J. | last2=Magazine | first2=E.S. | title=Saveur: The New Comfort Food: Home Cooking from Around the World | publisher=Chronicle Books LLC | year=2011 | isbn=978-1-4521-0539-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fXR9hz2Gu18C&pg=PA124 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=124}}</ref> |- | [[Naga Morich#Culinary usage|Naga doner kebab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | One of the most well-known Bangladeshi kebabs, commonly eaten in [[East London]], [[England]]. It is made of meat cooked on a vertical rotisserie, and then drizzled with the [[Naga morich]]. It is also known to be the most spiciest kebab due to the presence of the chilli. It can be fused with the Shatkora kebab as well (see below). |- | Reshmi kebab | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | Minced chicken<ref>{{cite book | title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide Delhi, Agra and Jaipur | publisher=DK Publishing | series=EYEWITNESS TRAVEL GUIDES | year=2015 | isbn=978-1-4654-4945-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ho0pCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA246 | access-date=May 22, 2018 | page=246}}</ref> adequately seasoned and then barbecued on a charcoal grill |- | [[Shami kebab]] | [[File:4th October 2012 Shami Kebab.jpg|127px]] | Normally made of minced meat, with paste of lentils and chopped onion and coriander and green chillies usually added to the mixture, which is kneaded in a disc-like shape and fried. Best results are obtained when fried in [[ghee]]. In some places, a binding agent is used to keep the kebab together. Meat can also be replaced with egg, known as Dim Kebab or Enda Kebab. |- | [[Citrus macroptera#Culinary uses|Shatkora doner kebab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | One of the most well-known Bangladeshi kebabs, commonly eaten in [[East London]], [[England]] as well as other areas with a high [[Bangladeshi diaspora]]. It is made of meat cooked on a vertical rotisserie, and then drizzled with the [[Shatkora]] plant. It is also known as the Hatkora or Hatkhora doner in [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]]. It can be fused with the Naga doner kebab as well (see above). |- | [[Seekh kebab]] | [[Image:Pakistani Food Beef Kabobs.jpg|127px]] | Prepared with [[Ground meat|minced meat]] with spices and grilled on skewers.<ref>{{cite book | last=Raichlen | first=S. | last2=Fink | first2=B. | title=The Barbecue! Bible | publisher=Workman Pub. | year=2008 | isbn=978-0-7611-4944-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FWKxatrLCjYC&pg=PA246 | access-date=May 22, 2018 | page=246}}</ref> It is often served with a Bengali sauce known as [[Raita]] or [[mint sauce]]. |- |}
==China== {{Main|Chinese cuisine}} {| class="wikitable sortable" width="100%" ! Name ! class="unsortable"| Image ! Description |- | ''[[Chuanr]]'' | [[File:Barbecued lamb sticks.jpg|127px]] | |[[Uyghur language|Uyghur]]: ''Kewap'', [[Chinese language|Chinese]]: 串儿 ''[[Chuanr]]'' or 羊肉串 ''Yangrouchuan'' — The most popular Xinjiang dish in China: chunks of mutton or mutton fat pierced on metal (or wood or bamboo) skewers, grilled on a coal-fired barbecue, and served with [[cumin]] and [[Chili pepper|chili]] paste. Across Xinjiang, and neighbouring regions such as Kyrgyzstan, the mutton fat is valued equivalent to or more than the meat itself, as it provides energy during the harsh winter months. It has also become a popular street food all over north and west China, where a wide variety of foods are cooked in such a manner. Chuanr was traditionally made from lamb (yáng ròu chuàn, 羊肉串), which is still the most common, but now, chicken, pork, beef, and seafood are used. It is typically roasted over charcoal or electric heat, but it is sometimes cooked by deep frying in oil (popular in Beijing). |}
==Cyprus== {{Main|Cypriot cuisine}} {| class="wikitable sortable" width="100%" ! Name ! class="unsortable"| Image ! Description |- | ''[[Sheftalia]]'' | [[File:Foukou.jpg|127px]] | A traditional [[Cypriot cuisine|Cypriot]] sausage made of ground pork or lamb and wrapped in caul fat that is served alone or in a pita, usually with tomato, cucumber, parsley, and lemon |- | ''[[Souvlaki]]'' | [[File:Souvlaki Platter.jpg|127x127px]] | Skewers consisting of pork, chicken or lamb that is barbecued.<ref>{{cite book | title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide: Cyprus | publisher=DK Publishing |year=2010 | isbn=978-0-7566-7405-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ooygPMx6iAsC&pg=PA174 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=174}}</ref> Pictured is a souvlaki platter. Souvlaki is described in the ''Oxford Companion to Food'' as a type of kebab that is part of the heritage of Islam.<ref name="Oxford Companion"/> |}
==Greece== {{Main|Greek cuisine}} {| class="wikitable sortable" width="100%" ! Name ! class="unsortable"| Image ! Description |- | [[Gyros]] | [[File:Gyros C5878.jpg|127px]] |Introduced to Athens in the 1950s by immigrants from Turkey and the Middle East, ''[[Gyro (food)|gyros]]'' was originally known simply as döner kebab.<ref name="Street Foods">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QQgwVl22fXkC&pg=PA6|title=Street Foods|publisher=Karger Medical and Scientific Publishers|year=2000|isbn=978-3-8055-6927-9|pages=6|chapter=Greek Street Food Vending: An Old Habit Turned New|author1-last=Matalas|author1-first=Antonia-Leda|author2-last=Yannakoulia|author2-first=Mary|editor1-last=Simopoulos|editor1-first=Artemis P.|editor2-last=Bhat|editor2-first=Ramesh Venkataramana}}</ref> Made from chopped meat, usually pork or chicken, formed into a large loaf for slow-roasting on a vertical rotisserie cooker, the auto-donner. (See also [[doner kebab]].) Thin portions are shaved off and served in a pitta bread with onion and Greek yogurt-cucumber-garlic sauce, [[tzatziki]]. Popularized in US by Greek restaurateurs in the [[Greektown, Chicago]] neighborhood. |- |''[[Souvlaki]]'' | |In the 1960s, vendors began selling dishes in the same style as [[gyros]], made with [[souvlaki]], which resembles Turkish shish kebab, but is usually made with pork.<ref name="Street Foods"/> Souvlaki (''skewer'') consists of small skewers of meat, barbecued, then served plain, in a pitta sandwich, or with salad. Chicken<ref>{{cite book | last=Flores | first=E.K. | title=Adventures in Chicken: 150 Amazing Recipes from the Creator of AdventuresInCooking.com | publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt | year=2016 | isbn=978-0-544-55821-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e060DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA115 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=115}}</ref> and lamb are also sometimes used. It is sometimes served on a skewer, or as a dinner in combination with rice, potatoes, and tzatziki sauce. In Athens, it is called ''kalamaki'', with ''souvlaki'' referring to both gyros and kalamaki. Souvlaki is described in the ''Oxford Companion to Food'' as a type of kebab that is part of the heritage of Islam.<ref name="Oxford Companion"/> |}
==India== {{Main|Indian cuisine}} {| class="wikitable sortable" width="100%" ! Name ! class="unsortable"| Image ! Description |- | [[Bihari cuisine#Non-vegetarian cuisine|Bihari kabab]] | [[File:Bihari Kabab.JPG|127px]] | Skewered pieces of meat [[Marination|marinated]] in spice. Originally a dish from the non-vegetarian cuisine, Muslims invented Bihari kabab of the North Indian state of [[Bihar]] as it is made out of beef . It has spread to other countries.<ref name="Bihari kabab"/> |- | Boti kebab | [[File:Boti and shesh kebab.jpg|127px]] | A [[mutton]] kebab.<ref>{{cite book | last=Singh | first=S. | title=India. Ediz. Inglese | publisher=Lonely Planet | series=Country Guide Series | year=2009 | isbn=978-1-74220-347-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vK88ktao7pIC&pg=PA262 | language=tr | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=262}}</ref> Boti kebab is pictured at the bottom of the image |- | Achari Tikka | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | | |- | [[Chicken tikka]] | [[File:Chicken Tikka (1).jpg|127px]] | Another tandoori kebab, made of cubed chicken marinated with yogurt and spices<ref name="Oseland 2011 124"/> |- | [[Dora kabab]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Dora kabab | website=Khaleej Times | date=October 22, 2015 | url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/lifestyle/food/recipe/dora-kabab | access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=India Today | publisher=Thomson Living Media India Limited | issue=v. 26 | year=2001 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c1BDAAAAYAAJ | access-date=May 26, 2017|page=163}}</ref> | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | |- | [[Galawat kabab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | A variant of [[Shami kebab]] made without any admixture or binding agents and comprising just the minced beef (Muslim origin) and the spices. Speciality of Lucknow. |- | [[Hariyali kabab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | [[Punjab region|Punjabi]] style chicken [[tikka (food)|tikka]] or kabab made with combination of [[Mentha|mint]] and [[coriander]] |- | [[Kakori kabab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | Made of minced beef meat with spices, a specialty of Muslims of Lucknow & Delhi |- | [[Galauti kebab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | |A [[Smoking (cooking)|smoked]] patty prepared using leg of lamb that includes onion, garlic, ginger, saffron and spices, which is cooked on a griddle<ref>{{cite book | last=Kraig | first=B. | last2=Sen | first2=C.T. | title=Street Food Around the World: An Encyclopedia of Food and Culture | publisher=ABC-CLIO | year=2013 | isbn=978-1-59884-955-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9XCjAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA176 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=176}}</ref> |- | [[Hariyali kebab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | A vegetarian kebab prepared using lentils and spinach<ref>{{cite web | title=8 meatilicious kebabs you must try out immediately | website=India Today | date=May 11, 2016 | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/8-kebabs-india-list-boti-galauti-hariyali-kakori-tangri-burrah-shami-reshmi-delhi-lucknow-hyderabad-mumbai/1/665611.html | access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Banerji | first=C. | title=Eating India: An Odyssey into the Food and Culture of the Land of Spices | publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing | year=2008 | isbn=978-1-59691-712-5 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XfjOQfPtmw0C&pg=PA125 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=125}}</ref> |- | [[Tangri kebab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> |Chicken legs roasted on open fire with hot spices and laced with butter or [[ghee]]<ref>{{cite book | last=Chaturvedi | first=A. | last2=Kanwar | first2=D. | last3=Sengupta | first3=R. | title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide: Delhi, Agra and Jaipur | publisher=DK Publishing | year=2013 | isbn=978-1-4654-1492-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RV_yAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA253 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=253}}</ref> |- | [[Kastoori kebab]]<ref>{{cite book | last=Kalra | first=J.I.S. | last2=Das Gupta | first2=P. | title=Prashad: Cooking with Indian Masters | publisher=Allied Publishers Private Limited | series=First Edition | year=1986 | isbn=978-81-7023-006-9 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-UFwsluKqM8C&pg=PA20 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=20}}</ref> | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | |- |- | [[Dahi ke kabab]]<ref>{{cite book | last=Kapoor | first=S. | last2=Kapoor | first2=A. | title=Marwari Vegetarian Cooking | publisher=Popular Prakashan | year=2009 | isbn=978-81-7991-399-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vHgAdnnnKzYC&pg=PA25 | language=de | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=25}}</ref> | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | |- | [[Burra kebab]]<ref>{{cite book | last=World | first=E.Y. | last2=Siciliano-Rosen | first2=L. | last3=Rosen | first3=S. | title=Delhi Food and Travel Guide: The inside scoop on the best North Indian foods in Delhi | publisher=Eat Your World | series=107 | year=2014 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NYfeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT51 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=pt51}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide: Delhi, Agra & Jaipur | publisher=DK Publishing | year=2015 | isbn=978-1-4654-4945-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ho0pCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA248 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=248}}</ref> | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | |- | Kalmi kebab | [[File:Kalmikabab.jpg|127px]] | A chicken kebab.<ref>{{cite book | title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide: Delhi, Agra & Jaipur | publisher=DK Publishing | year=2015 | isbn=978-1-4654-4945-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ho0pCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA246 | access-date=May 26, 2017 | page=246}}</ref> Kalmi kebab is pictured on the left in the image. |- | [[Paneer kabab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | Vegetarian kebab |- | [[Reshmi kabab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|127px]] --> | A traditional kebab of [[Mughlai cuisine]] that is prepared with marinated chicken, lamb or beef<ref>{{cite web | url=http://allrecipes.com/recipe/reshmi-kebab-silken-kebabs/ | title=Reshmi Kebab (Silken Kebabs) | publisher=Allrecipes.com | accessdate=2 November 2014}