==Iran== {{Main|Iranian cuisine}} {| class="wikitable sortable" width="100%" ! Name ! class="unsortable"| Image ! Description |- | [[Berenj goje kabab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | |- | [[Chelow kabab]] (rice with kebab) | [[File:Kebab.jpg|120px]] | Is one of the most common forms of serving kebab in Iran which combines a variety of Persian kebabs with [[saffron]]ed [[Basmati]] [[rice]], [[lavash]] (a paper-thin [[bread]]), grilled [[tomato]], raw [[onion]]s, [[bell pepper]]s, [[mushroom]]s and [[sumac]] and often a side of salad shirazi, [[Tzatziki|mast-o-khiar]] and [[doogh]] (nowadays [[carbonation|carbonated]]). An old Iranian tradition is to break a raw egg yolk over the rice, along with plenty of butter, just before serving, but not many follow this tradition anymore. |- | [[Dandeh kebab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | |- | [[Ghaz kabab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | |- | [[Joujeh kabab]] | [[File:Juje kabab 2.jpg|120px]] | Grilled chicken on skewers |- | [[Kabab bakhtiari]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Combination of Jujeh kabab and kabab barg |- | [[Kabab barg]] | [[File:Kababi alborz2.jpg|120px]] | Grilled marinated sirloin. |- | [[Kabab barreh]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Grilled lamb, typically marinated in yogurt with parsley |- | [[Kabab chenjeh]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Grilled lamb prepared similar to shish kebab, without the vegetables |- | [[Kabab digi]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Pan Kabab |- | [[Kabab hosseini]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Lamb or beef cooked on skewers with onions, tomatoes and green peppers |- | [[Kabab isphahani]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | |- | [[Kabab Jigar-o Del-o Gholveh]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Heart, liver, and kidney |- | [[Kabab kermanshahi]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | |- | [[Kabab koobideh]] | [[File:Kabab1.jpg|120px]] | Ground beef or lamb (usually sirloin), often mixed with [[parsley]] and chopped onions |- | [[Kabab kurdi]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Ground lamb or beef, onions, garlic, and tomatoes |- | [[Kabab loghmeh]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Minced lamb meatballs first fried and the grilled over charcoal fire, eaten with chopped parsley, chopped onions, and sumac. A summer outing favorite |- | [[Kabab mahitabeh]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Pan fried Kabab |- | [[Kabab rashti]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Also known as [[Kabab Shomali]], includes almond & pistachio & barberry |- | [[Kabab shamshiri]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | It is a kabab with kabab-barg on one side of skewer and kabab-kubideh on the other |- | [[Kabab shirazi]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | |- | [[Kabab soltani]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Combination of kabab koobideh and kabab barg |- | [[Kabab torsh]] | | ([[Gilan Province|Gilan]], northern Iran) Also called (tursh-e-kabab) grilled beef marinated in a mixture of pomegranate juice, crushed walnuts, parsley, crushed garlic, and olive oil |- | [[Kabab va nun]] ('Kabab with bread') | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | |- | [[Kabab vaziri]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Combination of kabab joojeh and kabab koobideh skewers |- | [[Kabab-e donbalan]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Lamb testicles kabab<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.de/books?id=_Kbj21wrwwEC&pg=PT27&lpg=PT27&dq=Kabab+donbalan&source=bl&ots=l1fpFlkdWp&sig=aH-Bv3KriS4POYn6fLlommvmD_c&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Kabab%20donbalan&f=false |title=A Persian Odyssey: Iran Revisited |last=Yelda |first=Rami |publisher=AuthorHouse |year=2012}}</ref> |- | [[Kababe shandiz]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | |- | [[Sonnati kabab]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | |}
