Beyti]] in [[Istanbul]] and particularly popular in Turkey's larger cities.<ref name=skylife>{{cite journal |url=http://www.thy.com/en-INT/skylife/archive/en/2000_12/konu4.htm#1 |title=Three Renowned Turkish Restaurants: Beyti Meat Restaurant |journal=Skylife - Turkish Airlines magazine |issue=12|year=2000 |pages=1–4}}</ref> |- | [[Bostan kebabı]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Lamb and aubergine casserole.<ref name=JHFEHJBAAH/> |- | [[Cağ kebabı]] (spoke kebab) | [[File:Cağkebabı5.jpg|120px]] | Cubes of lamb roasted first on a cağ (a horizontal [[Rotisserie|rotating spit]]) and then on a skewer, a specialty of [[Erzurum]] region with recently rising popularity |- | [[Çardak kebabı]]<ref name="Atabay">{{cite book|author=Banu Atabay|title=Mütevazi Lezzetler Deutsch|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DYaXAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA98|publisher=Banu Atabay|pages=98–|id=GGKEY:QQKUPZ6WZ7J}}</ref> | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Stuffed lamb meat wrapped in a [[crepe]] or [[filo]]. |- | [[Ciğer kebabı]] (liver kebab) | [[File:Çöp_şiş.jpg|120px]] | Lamb liver kebab on a skewer (a.k.a. ''ciğer şiş'') |- | [[Çökertme kebabı]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Sirloin veal kebap stuffed with [[yogurt]] and potatoes |- | [[Çöp şiş]] (small skewer kebab) | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | A specialty of [[Selçuk]] and [[Germencik]] near [[Ephesus]], pounded boneless meat with tomatoes and garlic marinated with black pepper, [[thyme]] and oil on wooden skewers<ref name="AHBADADDED"/> |- | [[Doner kebab]] | [[File:Döner in Istanbul (01.10.2008).jpg|120x120px]] |- | [[İskender kebap]] | [[File:İskender kebap.JPG|120px]] | Döner kebap served with [[yogurt]], tomato sauce and [[butter]], originated in [[Bursa]]. The kebab was invented by İskender Efendi in 1867. He was inspired from Cağ kebab and turned it from horizontal to vertical. |- | [[İslim kebabı]] (stew) | [[File:İslim kebabı.jpg|120px]] | Another version of the [[Patlıcan kebabı|aubergine kebab]] without its skin, marinated in sunflower oil<ref name=JHFEHJBAAH /><ref name=AHBADADDED/> |- | [[Kağıt kebabı]] | [[File:Kagıt kebabı.jpg|120px]] | Lamb (or veal) cooked in a paper wrapping<ref name=AHBADADDED/> |- | [[Kılıç şiş]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Brochette of swordfish<ref name=JHFEHJBAAH/> |- | [[Şiş köfte]] | [[File:Köfte kebabs.jpg|120px]] | Also known as Shish köfte – minced lamb meatballs with herbs, often including [[parsley]] and [[Mentha|mint]], on a stick, grilled |- | [[Kuyu kebabı]] (pit kebab) | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Prepared from the goat it is special for [[Aydın]] region, similar to [[tandır kebabı]] |- | [[Kuzu şiş]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Shish kebap prepared with marinated milk-fed lamb meat |- | [[Manisa kebabı]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | This [[Manisa]] region version of the kebab is smaller and flat size shish meat on the sliced [[Flatbread|pide]] bread, flavored with butter, and stuffed with tomato, garlic and green pepper. |- | [[Orman kebabı]] (forest kebab) | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Lamb meat on the bone and cut in large pieces mixed with carrots, potatoes and peas<ref name=JHFEHJBAAH/> |- | [[Patates kebabı]]<ref name="Sözen2005">{{cite book|author=Metin Sözen|title=Taşın belleği Mardin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K7QVAQAAIAAJ|year=2005|publisher=Yapı Kredi Kültür Sanat Yayıncıkık|isbn=978-975-08-1029-9}}</ref> | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Beef or chicken mixed with potatoes, onions, tomato sauce and bay leaves |- | [[Patlıcan kebabı]] (aubergine kebab) | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | A unique kebap meat marinated in spices and served with [[aubergines]], hot pide bread and a yogurt sauce<ref name=AHBADADDED/> |- | [[Şiş kebap|Şiş kebabı]] | [[File:Şiş kebap and pilav.jpg|120px]] | Prepared with fish, lamb or chicken meat on thin metal or reed rods, grilled<ref name=JHFEHJBAAH/><ref name=AHBADADDED/> |- | [[Şiş tavuk]] | [[File:Shish Tawooq - Turkish Cuisine.jpg|120px]] | Also known as Tavuk şiş or – [[Yogurt]]-[[marinate]]d chicken grilled on a stick<ref name=AHBADADDED>The Complete Book of Turkish Cooking , A.Algar (1985) {{ISBN|0-7103-0334-3}}</ref> |- | [[Sivas kebabı]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Associated with the [[Sivas]] region, similar to Tokat kebab but especially lamb ribs are preferred and it also differs from Tokat kebabı on the point that there are no potatoes inside |- | [[Tandır kebabı]] (tandoor kebab) | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Lamb pieces (sometimes a whole lamb) baked in an oven called a [[Tandoor|tandır]], which requires a special way of cooking for hours. Served with bread and raw onions.<ref name=JHFEHJBAAH/> |- |[[Tantuni]] |[[File:Tantuni.jpeg|frameless|133x133px]] |Tantuni is a [[Spice|spicy]] [[dürüm]] consisting of [[Julienning|julienne cut]] [[beef]] or sometimes [[Lamb (meat)|lamb]] [[Stir-fry|stir-fried]] on a [[Tava|sac]] with a hint of [[cotton oil]]. It is a specialty of the city of [[Mersin]], [[Turkey]]. |- | [[Tas kebap]] (veal stew) | [[File:Tas kebap, pilav and cacik.jpg|127px]] | Stewed meat in a bowl, beginning with the cooking of the vegetables in butter employing a method called yağa vurmak, ("butter infusion"), before the meat itself is cooked in the same grease |- | [[Testi kebabı]] (earthenware-jug kebab) | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Ingredients are similar to [[çömlek kebabı]], prepared in a [[testi]] instead of a [[güveç]], generally found in Central Anatolia and the Mid-Western Black Sea region |- | [[Tire meatballs|Tire kebabı]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Minced meat cooked on sheesh and served with maydanoz and sauce, on top of special tire bread |- | [[Tokat kebabı]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | Associated with the [[Tokat]] region, it is made with marinated lamb, grilled inside an oven, together with aubergines, tomatoes, potatoes, entire onions and garlics and served over a special flatbread called ''lavaş'' (a thicker yufka) and softened with the juice of the meat and tomatoes. |- | [[Urfa kebabı]] | <!--[[File:EXAMPLE|120px]] --> | From [[Urfa]], similar to Adana kebab, but not spicy |- |Vali Kebabı (Governor Kebab) |[[File:Vali kebabı.jpg|120px]] | |}
